"&#xa0;\nWritten evidence from the CBI (SRN 055)\n&#xa0;CBI Written Evidence for Transport Select Committee Inquiry on the Strategic Road Network&#xa0;Long-term funding reform of the roads network represents a crucial building block of a UK economy fit for the 21st century&#xa0;&#xa0;Figure 1 Coalition Government planned PSNI compared to Labour 2010 Budget proposal\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n              &#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;Figure 2 Public \nIn\nvestment\n as a % of GDP, 1990-2010\n&#xa0;While government has started to address the problems, the recent Road Command Paper does not go far enoughA new model of private investment is needed to improve the quality of the network and place the needs of the user at the heart of reform &#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nThere are crucial future steps government can take now to pave the way towards long-term reform of the roads network, while maximising current investment plans\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nCompleting all feasibility studies for road and rail projects outlined in the Spending Round and committing to plans for delivery;\n\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nConducting an audit of the state of the roads network and \nits costs to operate, so we \nhave the means for a serious discussion about private finance after 2015.\nNovember 2013\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n2\n&#xa0;\n \nGlobal competitiveness report 2013-14, \nWorld Economic Forum, 2013.\n \nBold thinking: A model to fund our future roads\n, CBI, October 2012.\n \nRAC Foundation: CSR/Infrastructure Announcement\n, June 2013\n              \n              \n              \n              \n              \n                                    http://www.racfoundation.org/media-centre/csr-infrastructure-announcement.\n \nThe \nEddington\n Transport Study\n, Sir Rod \nEddington\n for HM Treasury, December 2006.\n \nFuel for Thought: \nThe\n What, why and how of motoring taxation\n, The Institute of Fiscal Studies reported sponsored by RAC foundation, May 2012.\n \nThe rise of the regulated asset base model, \nDr. Matt \nFirla-Cuchra\n, KPMG UK: http://www.kpmg.com/global/en/issuesandinsights/articlespublications/insight-magazine/pages/rise-of-regulated-asset-based-model.aspx \n \nMaking your journey easier\n, Network Rail Control Period 4, Delivery Plan Update, 2012.\n \nDepartment for Transport Press Release\n \nhttp://www.gov.uk/government/news/80-million-to-tackle-more-pinch-points-on-local-roads\n, 27th September 2013.\n&#xa0;\n"